Reusability Rules

When to Extract a Shared Primitive

The "rule of three" applies — inline the first time, duplicate the second
time, extract on the third. Don't speculatively build shared components for
code that exists in one place.

Signs a primitive should be extracted:

Three or more components share the same JSX shape with different children
Three or more hook files have nearly identical mutation patterns
The same 10+ line block of utility code appears in multiple files
A CRUD pattern (form → validate → save → invalidate) is repeated per resource

Frontend Primitives (frontend/src/components/ui/)

CrudRow — horizontal row wrapper with a trash button slot. Used by any
editable list item (budget income/expense, accounts, debts). Takes children
(the editable fields) and an onDelete callback.

EditableField — text/number/date input that saves on blur only if changed.
Used wherever a field should auto-save without a Save button. Props:
value, onSave, type, inputMode, align, className.

Modal, Drawer, Card, Button, Badge, EmptyState, PriorityPip — already exist.
Any new page-level primitive with more than one caller lives here.

Do not put feature-specific UI in components/ui/. BudgetSummaryPanel belongs
in components/budget/. ProjectsPanel belongs in components/productivity/.

Factory Hooks (frontend/src/hooks/)

useResourceMutation(queryKey, apiFn) — wraps TanStack Query's useMutation and
invalidates the queryKey on success. All resource create/update/delete hooks
should be one-liners built on this:

export const useUpsertAccount = () =>
  useResourceMutation(['budget-accounts'], budgetApi.upsertAccount);

Never inline useMutation + useQueryClient + invalidateQueries again — it's
always the same five lines. Use the factory.

When a mutation needs special handling (optimistic updates, onError side
effects, custom success logic), inline useMutation for that one case. Don't
expand useResourceMutation with options — keep it single-purpose.

Backend Controller Splits

Rule of thumb: one controller per resource. A controller should not exceed
~500 lines. When it approaches that, split by resource.

Good:
- BudgetController — budget_months, income, expenses, copy-previous
- AccountController — budget_accounts
- DebtController — budget_debts

Bad:
- BudgetController handling months + accounts + debts + schema migrations
  (this is what grew to 942 lines before splitting)

Controllers share patterns via private helpers within their own file.
Repositories share patterns via a future BaseRepository (not yet added).
Don't premature-extract shared controller logic — let duplication appear
three times first.

Reusable API Patterns

All list endpoints return { items: [...], total?: number } or a plain array
depending on whether pagination applies. Paginated: { items, total, page, per_page }.
Non-paginated: plain array T[].

All upsert endpoints accept { id?: number, ...fields } — if id is present,
update; otherwise create. Return the updated/created resource.

All delete endpoints return { deleted: true } or the refreshed list.

When these three patterns are followed, useResourceMutation and TanStack Query
work with no custom wrapping.

What Not to Reuse

Don't extract:
- A component used in exactly one place, even if it's long — splitting for
  its own sake hurts readability
- Utility functions with fewer than three callers — leave them co-located
- "Configuration" objects that would need to be imported and customized
  in every call site — inline config is often clearer
- Styling wrappers like <PageContainer> when Tailwind classes do the job

A good sign code is too abstract: the shared version is longer than the
three duplicated versions would be, or the shared version has many optional
props that encode the different use cases.

File Size Alarm Thresholds

When any file exceeds these limits, split or extract:

- PHP controller: 500 lines
- React page: 400 lines
- React component: 250 lines
- Hook file: 150 lines
- Utility module: 200 lines

These are soft limits — a file can exceed them if the content is genuinely
cohesive. But reaching them should prompt the question: "is there a natural
split here?"
